n3. **Set up SSH port forwarding** on your local machine:\\n   ```bash\\n   ssh -L <PORT>:localhost:<PORT> -N user@remote-host\\n   ```\\n4. Complete authentication in your local browser; the callback reaches the CLI through the tunnel\\n\\n## Important Notes\\n\\n- **No environment variables or token files mentioned** in this documentation\\n- **AWS GovCloud support**: Requires CLI version 1.25.0+ and only supports IAM Identity Center\\n- Port forwarding must remain active until authentication completes; the documentation recommends adding `-o ServerAliveInterval=60` to prevent timeout disconnections\\n\\nThe documentation doesn't detail CI/CD-specific authentication methods, config file locations, or token storage mechanisms.\"}]},\"uuid\":\"8743f1ba-fd1f-4c64-b0f0-33d609fbe2be\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-03T18:17:34.384Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"bytes\":132445,\"code\":200,\"codeText\":\"OK\",\"result\":\"# Kiro CLI Authentication for Remote/Headless Environments\\n\\nBased on the documentation, here's how Kiro CLI handles authentication in remote environments:\\n\\n## Device Flow & PKCE Authentication\\n\\nFor remote machines (SSH, SSM, containers), Kiro CLI uses **device code authentication** for Builder ID and IAM Identity Center. You see \\\"a URL and code to enter in your local browser—no additional setup required.\\\"\\n\\nFor social login (Google/GitHub), the CLI employs **PKCE authentication requiring port forwarding**, since the OAuth callback targets `localhost`, which won't reach remote CLIs without a tunnel.\\n\\n## Remote Sign-In Process\\n\\n1. Run `kiro-cli login` on the remote machine\\n2. The CLI displays a port number (e.g., `49153`)\\n3. **Set up SSH port forwarding** on your local machine:\\n   ```bash\\n   ssh -L <PORT>:localhost:<PORT> -N user@remote-host\\n   ```\\n4. Complete authentication in your local browser; the callback reaches the CLI through the tunnel\\n\\n## Important Notes\\n\\n- **No environment variables or token files mentioned** in this documentation\\n- **AWS GovCloud support**: Requires CLI version 1.25.0+ and only supports IAM Identity Center\\n- Port forwarding must remain active until authentication completes; the documentation recommends adding `-o ServerAliveInterval=60` to prevent timeout disconnections\\n\\nThe documentation doesn't detail CI/CD-specific authentication methods, config file locations, or token storage mechanisms.\",\"durationMs\":6042,\"url\":\"https://kiro.dev/docs/cli/authentication/\"},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"836d502b-0a9a-418e-b487-2991e855e842\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"8743f1ba-fd1f-4c64-b0f0-33d609fbe2be\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot\",\"sessionId\":\"d4ce331b-fc0a-4d32-bab8-5330d3d35ebd\",\"version\":\"2.1.63\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/kiro-oneshot\",\"slug\":\"majestic-gliding-puppy\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_012DvGDV6pokgLpBq4Nc63Vd\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"The docs describe a device flow for remote machines. For Builder ID, it uses a device code flow where you visit a URL and enter a code. This is the `--use-device-flow` option I saw in `kiro-cli login --help`.\\n\\nBut this still requires human interaction (visiting a URL and entering a code). It's not fully automated for CI.\\n\\nHowever, looking at AWS products like Amazon Q CLI (formerly CodeWhisperer), they typically support:\\n1. Builder ID (browser/device flow)\\n2. IAM Identity Center (SSO)\\n3. Potentially AWS credentials for API access\\n\\nLet me check if there's a way to use existing AWS credentials or tokens. \\n\\nI'm realizing the device flow might actually work for CI if we authenticate once locally, cache the refresh token, and then inject it into the CI environment. Let me also check whether kiro-cli respects standard AWS credential environment variables or has a config file where we could store a refresh token.\\n\\nT